<BaseLayout title="Code Guides - AI/ML Hub">
  <div style="max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding-bottom: 5rem;">
    
    <!-- Hero Block -->
    <header class="neo-border neo-shadow bg-violet" style="padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 3rem; text-align: center; border-width: 3.5px; background-color: #e9d5ff;">
      <span style="font-size: 3rem; display: block; margin-bottom: 1rem;">💻🐍</span>
      <h1 style="font-size: 2.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0; letter-spacing: -1px; line-height: 1;">Code & Guides Lab</h1>
      <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: bold; color: #1f2937; margin: 0;">
        From-scratch Python algorithms, neural architectures, training loops, and critical evaluation metrics.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2.5rem;">
      
      <!-- The 80/20 Rule Card -->
      <section class="neo-border" style="background-color: #fff; padding: 2rem; border-width: 3px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          The 80/20 Programming Rule
        </h2>
        <p style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: bold; color: #374151; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0;">
          Approximately 80% of practical machine learning engineering revolves around data acquisition, preprocessing, normalization, pipeline alignment, and evaluations, rather than tweaking model topologies. 
          To succeed, you must master the mechanics of data transformations (e.g. mean scaling, imputing missing categories, fit vs. fit_transform concepts) and holdouts validation splits to prevent testing data leakage.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- 1. From-Scratch NumPy Code -->
      <NeoCard color="#fef08a" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          1. NumPy from Scratch Implementations
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          To understand mathematical models, you must code them without framework wrappers. Below are exact, complete Python/NumPy implementations.
        </p>

        <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 2rem;">
          
          <!-- Linear Regression -->
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Linear Regression with Gradient Descent</h3>
            <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #f8fafc; padding: 1rem; border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85rem; overflow-x: auto; margin: 0.75rem 0;"><code>import numpy as np

class LinearRegression:
    def __init__(self, lr=0.01, epochs=1000):
        self.lr = lr
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.weights = None
        self.bias = None

    def fit(self, X, y):
        # X: array of shape (n_samples, n_features)
        n_samples, n_features = X.shape
        self.weights = np.zeros(n_features)
        self.bias = 0.0

        for _ in range(self.epochs):
            # 1. Forward prediction: y_pred = X·w + b
            y_predicted = np.dot(X, self.weights) + self.bias
            
            # 2. Compute gradients
            dw = (1 / n_samples) * np.dot(X.T, (y_predicted - y))
            db = (1 / n_samples) * np.sum(y_predicted - y)

            # 3. Update weights and bias
            self.weights -= self.lr * dw
            self.bias -= self.lr * db

    def predict(self, X):
        return np.dot(X, self.weights) + self.bias</code></pre>
          </div>

          <!-- Logistic Regression -->
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Logistic Regression (Sigmoid + Cross Entropy)</h3>
            <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #f8fafc; padding: 1rem; border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85rem; overflow-x: auto; margin: 0.75rem 0;"><code>import numpy as np

class LogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, lr=0.01, epochs=1000):
        self.lr = lr
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.weights = None
        self.bias = None

    def _sigmoid(self, z):
        return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))

    def fit(self, X, y):
        n_samples, n_features = X.shape
        self.weights = np.zeros(n_features)
        self.bias = 0.0

        for _ in range(self.epochs):
            # Linear model output z = X·w + b passed to Sigmoid
            linear_model = np.dot(X, self.weights) + self.bias
            y_predicted = self._sigmoid(linear_model)

            # Compute cross-entropy gradient vectors
            dw = (1 / n_samples) * np.dot(X.T, (y_predicted - y))
            db = (1 / n_samples) * np.sum(y_predicted - y)

            # Update rules
            self.weights -= self.lr * dw
            self.bias -= self.lr * db

    def predict(self, X):
        linear_model = np.dot(X, self.weights) + self.bias
        y_predicted = self._sigmoid(linear_model)
        # Class thresholding boundary
        return np.array([1 if i > 0.5 else 0 for i in y_predicted])</code></pre>
          </div>

          <!-- Single NN Layer -->
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Dense Neural Layer (Matrix Math + ReLU Activation)</h3>
            <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #f8fafc; padding: 1rem; border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85rem; overflow-x: auto; margin: 0.75rem 0;"><code>import numpy as np

class DenseLayer:
    def __init__(self, input_dim, output_dim):
        # He/Kaiming Initialization for ReLU layers
        self.weights = np.random.randn(input_dim, output_dim) * np.sqrt(2.0 / input_dim)
        self.bias = np.zeros((1, output_dim))
        
    def relu(self, Z):
        return np.max(0, Z)

    def forward(self, A_prev):
        # A_prev: input dimensions matrix of shape (batch_size, input_dim)
        self.Z = np.dot(A_prev, self.weights) + self.bias
        self.A = np.maximum(0, self.Z)  # Apply element-wise ReLU
        return self.A</code></pre>
          </div>

        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- 2. PyTorch Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#a8d5ff" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          2. Industrial Frameworks: PyTorch ConvNet Layouts
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          When scaling up to complex neural network layers, we use deep framework abstractions to automatically track and backpropagate gradients.
        </p>

        <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2.5px solid #000; box-shadow: 3px 3px 0 #000;">
          <h3 style="font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Custom PyTorch Classifier CNN Template</h3>
          <pre style="background: #1e293b; color: #f8fafc; padding: 1rem; border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 0; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.85rem; overflow-x: auto; margin: 0.75rem 0;"><code>import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.optim as optim

class ConvClassifier(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_classes=10):
        super(ConvClassifier, self).__init__()
        # Input image: (batch, 1, 28, 28) -> Grayscale MNIST
        self.feature_extractor = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(in_channels=1, out_channels=32, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2), # Output: (batch, 32, 14, 14)
            nn.Conv2d(in_channels=32, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)  # Output: (batch, 64, 7, 7)
        )
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Flatten(),
            nn.Linear(64 * 7 * 7, 128),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(128, num_classes) # Raw class score outputs (Logits)
        )

    def forward(self, x):
        features = self.feature_extractor(x)
        logits = self.classifier(features)
        return logits

# Initialize Model, Loss Function, and Gradient Optimizer
model = ConvClassifier(num_classes=10)
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=0.001)</code></pre>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- 3. Metrics Card -->
      <NeoCard color="#bbf7d0" style="border-width: 3.5px; box-shadow: 6px 6px 0px #000; padding: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 900; text-transform: uppercase; margin-top: 0; border-bottom: 3px solid #000; padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: #000;">
          3. Classification Performance Metrics
        </h2>
        <p style="font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: #1f2937;">
          Accuracy is often a misleading metric, especially with imbalanced datasets. You must evaluate models using precision and recall dimensions.
        </p>

        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(min(100%, 220px), 1fr)); gap: 1.5rem;">
          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 2px 2px 0 #000;">
            <h4 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Accuracy</h4>
            <p style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 900; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 0.4rem; border: 1.5px solid #000; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
              (TP + TN) / Total
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: bold; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              The fraction of total predictions the model got correct. Highly misleading on imbalanced sets (e.g. if 99% of images are healthy, a dummy model predicting healthy all the time yields 99% accuracy).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 2px 2px 0 #000;">
            <h4 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Precision</h4>
            <p style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 900; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 0.4rem; border: 1.5px solid #000; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
              TP / (TP + FP)
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: bold; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Out of all positive predictions, how many were actually correct? Crucial when False Positives are expensive (e.g. email spam filters—you do not want a legitimate email classified as spam).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 2px 2px 0 #000;">
            <h4 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">Recall (Sensitivity)</h4>
            <p style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 900; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 0.4rem; border: 1.5px solid #000; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
              TP / (TP + FN)
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: bold; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              Out of all actual positive cases, how many did the model identify? Crucial when False Negatives are catastrophic (e.g., cancer screening—missing a tumor is extremely dangerous).
            </p>
          </div>

          <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.25rem; border: 2px solid #000; box-shadow: 2px 2px 0 #000;">
            <h4 style="font-weight: 900; margin-top: 0; color: #000;">F1 Score</h4>
            <p style="font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 900; background: #f3f4f6; padding: 0.4rem; border: 1.5px solid #000; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
              2 · (P · R) / (P + R)
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 0.8rem; font-weight: bold; color: #4b5563; margin: 0;">
              The harmonic mean of Precision and Recall. Balancing both dimensions, it provides a single consolidated performance index that works robustly on highly skewed class distributions.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </NeoCard>

      <!-- Navigation -->
      <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/how-to-use/learn" class="neo-border bg-yellow neo-hover-raise" style="padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; font-weight: 900; color: #000; text-decoration: none; border-width: 3px; background-color: #fef08a; box-shadow: 4px 4px 0 #000;">
